@node Inserting a link from the clipboard
@section Inserting a link from the clipboard

@findex org-web-tools-extras-insert-link-for-clipboard-url
The function @code{org-web-tools-extras-insert-link-for-clipboard-url} retrieves the first URL from the kill ring (using @code{org-web-tools--get-first-url}), fetches the page title for that URL, and returns a fully formatted Org link in the form @samp{[[url][title]]}. It delegates the actual link construction to the internal @code{org-web-tools--org-link-for-url} function.

This function is designed to be called from an Org Capture template. When you copy a URL in a browser and invoke an Org Capture template that uses this function, it automatically creates a properly formatted link without requiring you to type the title manually. For example, you might use it in a capture template like this:

@lisp
(setq org-capture-templates
      '(("l" "Link" entry (file "~/links.org")
         "* %(org-web-tools-extras-insert-link-for-clipboard-url)\n")))
@end lisp

@node Extracting a page title
@section Extracting a page title

@findex org-web-tools-extras-org-title-for-url
The function @code{org-web-tools-extras-org-title-for-url} fetches the HTML content of a given URL, extracts the @samp{<title>} element, and returns the cleaned title string. It uses the @samp{plz} library to perform the HTTP request and @code{libxml-parse-html-region} to parse the HTML DOM@.

If the URL argument is omitted, the function defaults to the first URL found in the kill ring, making it convenient for quick programmatic lookups. If the HTTP request fails, the HTML cannot be parsed, or the page has no @samp{<title>} element, the function returns the fallback string @samp{"Downloaded webpage"} rather than signaling an error. Title cleanup is performed by @code{org-web-tools--cleanup-title}, which strips extraneous whitespace and normalizes the string for use in Org links.

